¬†@vriskaxtereziotp¬† I'm not vegan, but your comparison is completely flawed. You've picked out a few issues specific to certain crops and methods of growing them, these are hardly intrinsic problems to veganism. On the other hand, having to grow crops for both humans AND livestock is always going to be disastrous for the environment, there's no way around it. The energy transfer from crop to livestock to human is so much lower than from crop to human directly, so we end up using more land, WAY more water (yes even more than for almonds) and emitting a lot more.
Sorry for the rant, and again I agree it's stupid to criticize others for their choice to eat meat (as a mear-eater myself). But let's not fall under any delusion that veganism is just as bad as meat consumption for the environment.

¬†@vriskaxtereziotp¬†  I'm going to respectfully disagree with this. The problem with this argument is that it implies that vegans are the majority of almond consumers when they are like 1% of the population. Omnivores people eat almonds ya know.

The truth is, it takes a lot more resources to produce meat, and the emissions are much  higher when producing animal products,  It takes a lot of water and grain to raise thousands and thousands of animals that individually weigh over 1000 pounds. Comment:
¬†@darith770¬† The point of it being dogs is the big issue. There is a reason dogs and horses are off limits. Both dogs and horses have supported man kind as we survived the harshness of a pre-modern world. They helped us find food, explore new lands, plow fields and not to mention the companionship they provided our species. It‚Äôs out of respect that dogs and horses are taboo for food and leather. That‚Äôs what sets skinning dogs/puppies aside from wearing cow leather. I always found it less efficient that she skinned puppies instead of full grown dogs, but i assume that was just to make her more evil.

Side note, being a healthy vegan requires an insane amount of research and education. In order to get all the proper nutrients your body needs without meat or dairy is insanely difficult. Especially since it varies with age and other factors. That‚Äôs where the, ‚Äúunhealthy vegan‚Äù stereotype comes from. Some people just quit meat and dairy without researching what they need replace it with in their diet. They end up doing more harm to themselves than good. That‚Äôs why if you eat whatever you can, your body is more likely to get the nutrients it needs, junk food aside that is. So to chastise people for not spending dozens upon dozens of hours of research to properly eat a healthy vegan diet is unrealistic. Especially since there is little to no mainstream material provided to the public on how to do this. You can blame major food production companies and the medical field for this. They don‚Äôt want to take the hit to their pockets by educating the population on eating and staying healthy. Even the government plays a small role in this. 

The back and forth over the moral implications of eating meat and wearing leather vs skinning puppies is one to be had, but the attacks on other people‚Äôs character in an attempt to compare them to Cruella De Vil is disingenuous at best.  Also not saying you were doing this, but plenty of people in comments have been. She enjoyed the act of stealing and killing puppies, not just because of the money either. And as I mentioned before, she skinned puppies where as skinning dogs would produce a higher yield, as well as carry less moral baggage. For example, I support peoples right to eat meat, but i think eat veal(spelling?) is morally apprehensible. The calf is pinned up in a harness so it can‚Äôt walk/stand with the purpose of keeping it from forming muscles so that the meat is more tender. It‚Äôs one thing to eat an animal, it‚Äôs another thing to torcher it before you do.

Comment:
¬†@vriskaxtereziotp¬† - Almonds and Quinoa aren't a strictly vegan food, you know that right? Vegans only make up 2% of the population. That means majority of the consumption of these products comes from meat-eaters. That's bc almond milk & quinoa are health fads promoted by the Diet Industry. So the onus for these problematic foods falls on meat-eaters. But even when factoring the amount of water, fuel, and land used to grow/ship almonds & quinoa, they make up only a fraction of the environmental impact that dairy and meat have. You know how I know you're just regurgitating secondhand info you heard? Bc if you did actual research, you'd know the percentage of impact by those foods is inconsequential in the scope of meat & dairy. Not to mention that the millions of tons of manure from farm animals is creating runoff into our rivers & waterways, leading to hypoxic dead zones in our oceans. It's also causing air pollution resulting in higher incidences of asthma, pulmonary fibrosis, and lung cancer in communities near animal farms. The amount of desertification caused by cattle is nearly 40%! We've had to go overseas to find new farmland, bc the excess breeding & overpopulation of cattle is destroying the sustainability of our pastures. They're also destroying the ocean, bc cattle eat millions of tons of fish a year for Omega-3s, which results in overfishing. Up to 91% of Amazon deforestation stems from the building of cattle farms ‚Äî which leads to displacement & homelessness of indigenous people. Let's not forget the "corporate land grabs" in Africa, Thailand, and Cambodia by the meat industry. Oh I can keep going. There's SO many layers to the impact by animal agriculture. You have no idea! 

Does all of this mean you should go vegan? Not necessarily, but it DOES mean you should be thinking about cutting back your consumption of meat/dairy. They have the highest impact on the environment than any product in the world, and that includes fuel!

Comment:
¬†@julex5080¬† I don't want to tell anyone to stop eating meat. But it is honestly not healthy & you absolutely don't need it to survive. In fact.. considering how much food and water animals need to grow.. our meat consumption is going to lead us into a hunger crisis at some point. So.. we are not going to starve or lack any nutrients when we cut out meat.. on the contrary many people in the world are going to starve if we continue eating more and more meat.

In case you are interested:
-Vitamin B12 is being fed to animals (just like how Iodine is being added to salt) so that people take in enough of it. So it doesn't really make a difference whether you take a supplement yourself.. or you drink milk and take in the supplement that was given to the cow. In fact.. you probably have better control over how much vitamin b12 you're taking in if you're just taking the pill yourself.
-People don't need a lot of protein. It's a myth that vegans and vegetarians lack protein. There are plenty of vegan/vegetarian athletes. Meat may actually slow you down.
-Iron deficiency can be problematic.. to women. Men don't usually become iron deficient. In fact.. an iron overload is much more dangerous for men. Women should get their iron levels checked regularly.. even if they eat meat. We just lose a lot of iron due to menstruation and pregnancy. Eating bacon is not going to solve that. Those kind of processed meats are delicious.. yes.. but they are not rich in iron or other nutrients. You need to eat liver and s*** like that.

Comment: ¬†@julex5080¬† meat contains heme-iron which can be more easily absorbed by the human body than the iron found in plants. However, without a condition causing you to be unable to easily absorb iron, it will make no difference to your iron levels. If you do theoretically have a condition, having enough vitamin C (which everyone should regardless) will make it so you can absorb non-heme iron. As for B12, it‚Äôs not made in meat. B12 is produced by bacteria found in soil and on grass. It‚Äôs then passed from an animal (eating grass) into the human diet. However, this isn‚Äôt enough to sustain a human diet (most people have a B12 deficiency and don‚Äôt realise until they have a blood test) AND most farmed animals don‚Äôt even eat grass. B12 is therefore supplemented into livestock feed. The only difference between a vegan source of B12 and a non-vegan source is that vegans take the supplements directly (or it‚Äôs added to tofu, cereal etc), rather than giving it to the cows. Not only can we thrive on vegan diets, but they‚Äôre actually healthier by a landslide. Meat diets have a direct link to the global leading causes of death (stroke, coronary heart disease, type 2 diabetes, obesity etc) :)

Comment:
Well, here's the thing. I can agree I would enjoy a straight up villain in a film again... If they weren't the main focus. I know there are many films about terrible people just being terrible, but it either delves heavily into the psyche of that person, or we explore more of that persons life to the poi t where it's understandable what they are doing, though we don't like it.

However, in this film she is the character we follow, and learn the most about. This is her origin story, we see how she becomes who she becomes, she won't be misunderstood, she won't be an anti-hero. Where she will end up in this film IS pure evil. She will end up being the villain, even if she doesn't see it herself. The way I look at it is we will see a woman start from nothing, and end up down a very bad path that she can change before it gets to bad and she will choose the bad option, that is still evil. You don't get to skinning puppies because you look good in life and not be completely evil at that point, no matter how sympathetic you are at the start of your journey.

... Well, ok, I say all that, but in truth I don't know. I haven't seen the film, obviously, I'm just giving my best guess based off what I can gather from anything I've heard about this film. Maybe I'm wrong, but it just wouldn't make sense for them to make this a prequel instead of a retelling if they were going to make her misunderstood in the end.

Comment:
I know some people doesn't like the Maleficent movie series on how it turned out, but I think it's fine that Disney did it like that. 

First of all Fairies are not Good nor are they Evil to begin with, they are more neutral than we think, they are true to their natural type of existence, their views are vastly different to an ancient/medieval Human's point of view (cause Humans at that time focused on surviving everyday life, they lack education & worldly understanding that we modern people have, etc.)

Looking at the trailer I think they are going for the action, psychotic, strong woman, Villainess that Cruella is (maybe like the Female Fashionista version of Joker, Disney style). There is a possibly small/very minor sob story at the beginning, but  it'll probably get overshadowed very easily & fast by the rest of the movie.

I'm actually looking forward to Cruella's villainess side of story, she's a fascinating character.

Comment:
Unpopular opinion: Maleficent worked as a redeemable character. She didn‚Äôt just randomly curse Aurora for no reason. She was literally the one person in the entire kingdom who wasn‚Äôt invited to the ceremony. And notice how she has an army of monsters but it‚Äôs never mentioned in the story that she‚Äôs trying to take over the kingdom. They‚Äôre basically butlers. You could make the argument that she was just misunderstood, bullied, and resorted to using her powers for evil. Her and the three fairies were the only characters with a lot of personality throughout the film and therefore, there was a lot of creative freedom to take. 

Now, with Cruella, that freedom doesn‚Äôt exist. She wasn‚Äôt trying to get back at Anita for anything. She didn‚Äôt have some trauma that explained her desire to skin puppies for clothes. She just wanted to do so because she found it to be fashionable and there were no redeeming qualities to her. So, they could make a movie and tell her story in a compelling manner. However, it would have to stray even further from the source material. 

She‚Äôs not misunderstood like how you can argue with villains like Maleficent or Hades. She‚Äôs not a victim of her surrounds like Captain Hook or Ursula. She‚Äôs downright evil and I can‚Äôt comprehend how someone can spin this into a tale where she‚Äôs a sympathetic character. I saw someone comment that next they‚Äôll do one about the hunter from Bambi and that really isn‚Äôt a stretch. Both characters get satisfaction from killing innocent creatures for entertainment. There‚Äôs nothing redeemable there. Nothing.

Comment:
@Michael Kim Yes you're right about the original joker being far from what we got in Arthur Fleck. But, in that movie it doesn't make you sympthaize with him. You understand where he came from and sometimes it challenges people to feel a bit bad (like him getting beat up in the ally and killing the men who were bothering that girl in the subway). As the movie goes on we see how mentally unstable he is, we witness him do horrible things to people and the movie doesn't paint him as someone you should cheer for, he's crazy, he's unstable, he's the joker at the end of the film. Espicially when he's in that talk show, It's like being next to a phsycopath and you can't move away. That film perfectly told Joker's chracter as being a product of a horrible society of Gotham while also leaving him abigiously evil. 

Now, cruella, a DISNEY character. The trailer displays her as a feminist ahead of her time (quite ahead acutally). It's milking the "women are strong" message that other movies have done so much better and are actually more subtle. Reamking her charcater in this way is a mistake, they are going to make her misunderstood, Yes. But they are going to end up making her sympthatic. The disney logo that is there in every movie they made symbolizes a brand, a specific type of entertainment. Where they make their character, good or evil, as borderline family friendly as possible. They don't have the courage to make it into an actual Joker or Taxi Driver film where it will leave the character as amoral and disturbed. The trailer says it all on what they are focusing on: Women can do anything, Cruella is crying so you should be crying with her, fashion show cuz girls like dresses, and  the most ironically harmful message, women are crazy. This idea they had didn't come from someone who thought she was a good character to do a movie on, but from a group of men who felt like they should have a harley quinn movie and this is the only chracter that kinda fit the bill. When this movie comes out and it's an acutal gritty film (not talking about the pirates of the carribian "gritty") like an actual film about her descent into madness, then all of what I said will be completly wrong. Comment:
TL;DR Cruella is going to have to be heavily retconned in this origin story if audiences want to have any chance of sympathizing with her. No matter how sad a character's past is, not many are going to find skinning helpless puppies - or any animals - for dresses something easy to be sympathetic toward.

I kinda wonder how that's going to be handled honestly. Like obviously YOU have to make sympathetic in some way, so does she just make a 180 at the very end and become fully evil? I suppose they COULD go that route, but I find it hard to believe she will end up being a fully fledged villain in this simply because I don't know if Disney has the guts to make a film where the villain is the protagonist (i.e. look at what Disney did to Artemis Fowl who was supposed to be the protagonist AND the villain in the books, but Disney ruined him and made him a misunderstood good guy). And if they DO move forward with a 101 Dalmatians film, kinda wonder how she would be handled in that. I have a feeling this is more of a reboot of the character, where she will be more sympathetic without all the dog skinning. No matter how dark your past is, it's a pretty hard to get audiences to full on sympathize with someone who wants to murder puppies and turn them into dresses. She is going to have to be retconned in this film, or it just isn't going to work.

What if any of these were the murder victim? Of COURSE it'd be downplayed; they deserved it for committing unspeakable atrocities against humanity. And from those dramatic examples you can understand how it's easier to downplay and even sympathize with the taking of another human life; there are wicked people out there who sometimes do terribly wicked things to earn their fate. One of those wicked (and completely unsympathetic) things a person can do is the taking of an innocent life; animals are one of the most innocent forms of that life since they lack the proper sentience to be aware of any wrong they might commit in a human's eyes. So yes, it is INFINITELY easier to downplay a character killing other people because those people can be easily made deserving of such a fate compared to a character who kills puppies since puppies can never be made deserving of such a fate.

Comment:
Unpopular opinion:
This film works so much better if you treat it like a reimagining (like Maleficent), instead of trying to force it into being a prequel. 
Cruella's character is too different; she's not the villain (in the end she does the right thing, and no puppies die), and the dognapping even happens in the film. It honestly seems like she hit a low throughout the movie but by the end she's recovered and grown into a better person. 
Forcing it to be a prequel erases the entire point of the film, of her grappling with her identity after discovering her mother's narcissism and coming to an equilibrium by both accepting it in herself and controlling it in order to keep her adoptive family.
With this in mind I absolutely love this film! It's one of the best Disney has made in years.
Edit: Also Horace and Jasper are the biggest dog people in cinema in this version. They literally spend the entire time film adopting and kissing dogs. Get out of here trying to convince me they'd ever kill one when they almost abandoned Cruella over organizing an illegal concert.

I can forgive Disney if they find some way to make it so Luke didn't abandon the galaxy; didn't consider killing his Nephew cause he had a bad dream; and wasn't indirectly responsible for the first order; but those are my terms and if Disney can't do that; then perhaps fans like you will keep the Franchise alive; but I think it will be a shell of its former self.

Comment:
@Beauty As Being I'm not adding personal character traits to the original Maleficent, only addressing those demonstrated in the movie. To ignore the character's facial expressions and voice inflection in a movie would hide part of the original portrayal and intent of the writers/artists of the film. 

Even if we insist on finding symbolism in everything in the movie that's subjective. You might see the wheel to symbolize as time and fate, but symbolism interpretation can vary from person to person. You might see Aurora shipped away in fear to symbolize she was "removed from life", but that doesn't mean that is the only possible interpretation. Aurora hanging out with various animals can be interpreted that she surrounded herself with life. I didn't perceive Aurora as "freaking out" over meeting another human (the prince)... she didn't attack him or scream or cry for help... she was briefly a little startled, but she danced with him, sang with him, flirted with him and eventually watched the sun go down with him. A fire-breathing dragon is not a beast of nature, much less a symbol of nature. It's an unnatural mythical monster. Likewise spell-casting satanic magic "with all the powers of Hell" and curses are not part of nature, but far more often found in religions. Her satanic symbolism and statements act as a stark contrast to the family's christening of baby Aurora.

Comment:
This is the thing that kind of irks me. 

The entire point of a villain POV is to delve deeper into a villain who is the juxtaposition and foil of the hero, which is in a way highly dependent on the heroes' character. Cruella's entire shtick in 101 Dalmatians is that she's a crazy weirdo in contrast to the generic normal protagonist humans, there not being much character to use since the story was mostly centered around the Dalmatians with the humans kind of being secondary characters. Cruella is not only extremely simple as a character, but she isn't even relevant for most of the Dalmatian story until the second half (she's basically just a much less interesting Anton Ego role-wise).

If anything, if Disney wanted to do another Maleficent, a much better choice would have been Gargamel with The Smurfs since there's a lot of material and context to contextualize compared to "this crazy rich weirdo wants spotted pattern coats".

¬†@bobjones597¬† False. In reality, while processed fake meat is expensive, sure, plant-based whole-food is CHEAPER than animal products (and is much healthier than processed fake meat and real meat). E.g. in Australia, chicken mince is $12.00/kg, while red lentils are $3.50/kg. I.e. chicken is 3-4x the price of lentils.

One of the reasons for this is that the production of 1kg of plant protein requires less land, water and labour than 1kg of animal protein. Eating animals increases our risk of cancer, strokes, heart attacks, impotence, etc., so you might want to join us in encouraging everyone to switch to plant-based whole-food.

Beware, though, the meat industry is very rich and powerful and uses false advertising and political donations to politicians to get its way.

Comment:
¬†@Thundercleese1¬† You're welcome. :) It's not your fault, most people only know of Harley Quinn as a movie product/sex symbol, because that's how she's always introduced, portrayed and written; and she's definitely not the only one they do that to, unfortunately.
 Harley Quinn the character/persona, is never really worked in, validated, or even given her own space for personal development or individual purpose, outside of forwarding the plot. A lot of movie renditions of comics end up like that, the value of the production is lost because the focus is usually geared more towards focusing on the body of the actors(regardless of gender) and figuring out how to sexualize the modernized costumes they're meant to wear, in ways that "aren't too offensive" (the batsuit having nipples used to be quite the controversy.) After they have 'the look' achieved, everything else seems to go ignored, and the characters go flat and become recognized more for what the effort was put into: their appearance, and/or 1-2 personality traits they're given; for example, the (incredible) hulk, known now mostly for being a giant green mutated muscular shirtless man, who says "you wouldn't like me when I'm angry" and of course, "hulk smash" Barely a caricature of the original material, and because of that, everything suffers, the story, representation, sequels, fans, everything except box-office sales. 
I'm happy you're more interested in her character, I'm glad I didn't give away much, just in case you decide to check out the source material. Have a pleasant one. ‚ô•Ô∏è‚úåÔ∏è

Comment: ‚Äã¬†@maximuslordofdarknes¬† Disney not caring about progressivism is something I completely agree with. They show just enough progress to win over one side while playing safe as to not offend the other. They keep pandering to our nostalgia and making subpar remakes instead of making original stories. But even though I'm never gonna watch Cruella, I wouldn't necessarily call those who will watch it and other pseudo-feminist movies dumb; impressionable, sure, but not dumb. Comment:
movie is set in the 1960/70's. You first get introduced to Estella, a young girl who tries to be good. Like all children she is not perfect; however, Estella tries to please her single mother. Estella soon meets Horace and Jasper. They form a friendship, turned family and this is where the story truly begins. In this adaptation you will also meet Roger and Anita. 

The acting was great. The dynamic between Emma Stone (Estella later Cruella) and Emma Thompson (The Baroness) are amazing. (The other cast are all great as well.) I have no complaints. Both Estella and The Baroness are hard-working, talented in the fashion field; but, you wanna stay on the good sides of these two ladies. The Baroness is Estella's cut-throat boss later turned nemesis. The Baroness is a rockstar in the fashion world and Estella's Idol. This brings me to the costuming. 

The costuming has to win some awards. It was truly a work of art. As a guy who knows basically nothing about fashion it made me wish I did: because I felt like I would have appreciated it more. It was truly impressive especially the one scene with Cruella's train blowing in the wind. (When you see it you'll know what I mean!)

You know how the original 'Cruella' song says "to see her is to take a sudden chill' I did get a chill from Emma Stone a couple of times. Both these ladies were phenomenal! Speaking of the original song let me talk about the music. 

The soundtrack has all 70's songs. Most of these songs aren't huge hits but not obscure songs either most of the songs you will know. Many of the songs chosen are not originals but remakes. There are some original songs in the film as well. Band 'Florence and the Machine' has a song titled "Call Me Cruella". 

The music was used to convey a lot of emotion and used very well for the dark cinematography which starts out in black and white. Which is perfect! It is PG-13 I wouldn't recommend for children because it is a bit dark. 

How does Emma Stone compare to Glenn Close? I'm not sure! Emma Stone is supposed to be the same version that leads into Glenn Close. As I'm writing this I'm watching Glenn Close to compare and I can't. I think they are both great! 

What else can I say? This is definitely a woman empowerment movie. You may feel a little sad for Cruella; yet, you will still think she is evil! You will admire Estella for her hard work. It is over 2 hours and is much better than 2014's Maleficent.

Comment:
This movie is brilliant but there‚Äôs one nitpick I have about it.

The Baroness and Cruella are portrayed as having Cluster-B personality disorders. With the exception of psychopaths, who are born the way they are, all other Cluster-B personality disorders are made the way they are. 

This movie portrays Cruella having a Cluster-B personality disorder despite not being raised and abused by her biological Pathological Narcissist mother but instead by her non-Cluster-B genuinely kind, loving, and nurturing adopted mother. This sends an incorrect message that Cluster-B personality disorders are genetically inherited, which they are not.

Comment: This is an incredible movie! The acting was fantastic! I feel Cruella is a creative character to have but I believe her hair being two colors could signify multiple personality disorder. Now, I'm not diagnosing her but that is just my theory. If you watch the movie, you would see why I would think that based on her behavior. It seems she had a heart for the Dalmatians in this film. I'm a little curious as to what made her want to skin Dalmatians in 101 Dalmatians. I have watched the 101 Dalmatians live action that Disney Plus offers to know she wanted a new, stylish coat. I feel the issue lies deeper than that due to her childhood trauma and her genes. Everyone who watches the movie would know what I'm talking about if they've seen Cruella. I do hope they make a sequel to this movie that could explain some more details (I feel a sequel was hinted at the end). I already know what her name means but I would just like to see a remake of 101 Dalmatians that has more details such as maybe a flashback of her life that triggered her wanting to skin puppies.

Comment: ¬†@gavriellpasamonte¬† No, anti-heros aren‚Äôt villains. They're just rather plain characters who fall short of the expected chivalry, noble birth or good look that the audience normally expect from a protagonist. Anti-heroes are protagonists despite lacking the typical heroic qualities. For example, Bernard Shaw made Bluntschli the protagonist, even though he doesn‚Äôt have the traditional heroic features that another character Sergius has. In this case, we can call Bluntschli an anti-hero. Same goes for all the less than perfect protagonists we find in almost all modern literature and movies

Comment: It's a + and -- when a story has expectations built into it as this story does. When U luv something for its previous incarnations, to embrace a new vision isn't always easy as we quickly discovered. Yet as a stand alone it works wonderfully but it's not really a stand alone, is it? Still there's plenty of great moments altho the choice to TALK over the action for what felt like an eternity at the top and the Devil Wears Prada-ish relationship between Cruella and her mother the Baroness didn't quite work as well as it might have in our opinion in part b/c the mother role wasn't quite written as well as the Devil Wears Prada role and could have used M. Streep (perhaps) to give it those truly nasty, yet delicious sinister twists. Emma Thompson does well,, but it felt a wee bit of a stretch for her for the reasons noted. Shout out to Emma Stone who seemed to give a nod to Tim Curry's portrayal of Dr. Frank N' Furter in her portrayal of Cruella. If she was going to borrow from anyone for the creation of Cruella, T. Curry in Rocky Horror was a a very wise choice in our opinion. In short, worth seeing.
